{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774458114,"nonce":"s7HTxRGSDUY45dlB/9wtcf9/zPk=","title":"Part 1 analysis: feedback perturbation responses","message":"Umbrella: 297260c (Part 1)\n\n**Motivation:** Characterize the feedback correction loop by measuring how the network responds to transient impulse perturbations in position and velocity feedback channels. This reveals the gain and dynamics of the feedback controller without SISU context.\n\n**Approach:** Apply brief impulse perturbations (varying amplitude) to position and velocity feedback channels during center-out reaching. Decompose responses into movement-aligned (parallel/lateral) components and compute scalar measures (max force, deviation, velocity extremes). Visualize via violin plots across perturbation amplitudes and training perturbation standard deviations.\n\n**Status:** Module exists at `src/rlrmp/modules/analysis/part1/feedback_perts.py`. Uses feedbax `AlignedVars`, `ApplyFns`, and `Violins` primitives. Supports both random-direction and x/y-axis impulses.\n\n**References:** Cluff \u0026 Scott (2013) for feedback perturbation paradigm in reaching.","files":null}]}